<div1 title="Title Page" id="i">
<h1 id="i-p0.9" style="text-align: center;">Sower Applications Help 1.3</h1>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower &amp; ThML Viewer" id="ii">
<p id="ii-p1">Sower, and ThML Viewer are very similar applications. The primary
      difference is that Sower is designed to use Sower Modules for primary
      content while ThML Viewer uses ThML files. Both rely on Sower Modules, and
      ThML files for AutoDef data. Both are also designed so that the user
      interface is created through plug-ins. Alpha, Beta, and Gamma
      interface plug-ins are available for both programs, and each provides
      access to the available content in a different way so that users can
      choose the interface that is most comfortable for them. Below is some
      basic information on the user interfaces.</p>
    <ol id="ii-p2.1">
 <li id="ii-p2.2">AutoDef windows are pop-up windows that appear when a link has been
        clicked, or the mouse has been moved over a reference that the
        application recognizes, or a word that an entry can be found for in a
        dictionary etc. Moving the mouse into the AutoDef window will cause it
        to stay visible. The window can be scrolled to view content, if the
        contents are not copy protected it can be selected and copied, or
        printed. And AutoDef windows can have AutoDef windows. It may take
        practice to work with AutoDef windows, the advantage is automatic
        retrieval of information, and the ability to follow a stream of
        information up to the point where there is insufficient space for a
        window within a window. AutoDef can also use GeoLocation, or embedded
        map data to find relevant information for locations when moving the
        mouse within an image of a map.</li>
      <li id="ii-p2.4">Modules, and ThML files that AutoDef is allowed to retrieve can be
        enabled\disabled through the Preferences dialog.</li>
      <li id="ii-p2.6">When creating a bookmark selecting a section of text will the
        selection to be selected when the bookmark is activated later.</li>
      <li id="ii-p2.8">Once a bookmark has been created a note can be added, or edited with a
        left click on the item in the BookMarks panel.</li>
      <li id="ii-p2.10">Right click on a bookmark will pull up a menu that allows the bookmark
        to be deleted.</li>
      <li id="ii-p2.12">Use the Preferences dialog to:<br>
        <ul id="ii-p2.13">
 <li id="ii-p2.14">Set the location of libraries.</li>
          <li id="ii-p2.16">Default font size for content viewers, and AutoDef windows.</li>
          <li id="ii-p2.18">Select the user interface.</li>
          <li id="ii-p2.20">Select the theme.</li>
          <li id="ii-p2.22">Select the language.</li>
          <li id="ii-p2.24">Enable\disable saving the session at upon closing the application.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="ii-p2.28">The Alpha interface is a tabbed interface. The tab control can be
        split by dragging a tab to a different position in the window. Once a
        tab control has been split other tabs can be dragged onto any of the new
        tab controls. There can be any number of tab controls split off in this
        manner allowing the user to have multiple books viewable at the same
        time, and allowing the tab controls to be organized, and sized to the
        preferences of the user.</li>
      <li id="ii-p2.30">The Beta interface provides a single table of contents for all
        available content, and all content is displayed in the same window.</li>
      <li id="ii-p2.32">The Gamma interface is a tabbed interface in which content is divided
        into categories with a separate tab, and table of contents for each.</li>
      <li id="ii-p2.34">Sower is intended to provide content from Sower Modules. But, Sower
        can also display ThML files which when opened will be displayed in a
        separate tab control. </li>
    </ol>
    <p id="ii-p3"> Note: </p>
    <p id="ii-p5">ThML files exist in two forms. In one form it is split into multiple
      files, while in the other form everything exists in one large file (with
      the exception of any external media). ThML Viewer is designed to work with
      ThML files in the second form only. </p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Data File Editor" id="iii">
<p id="iii-p1">Sower Data File Editor is used to edit Sower's table based data files
      (sdf), and is similar to Sower Theme Editor, and Sower Translation Editor.
      It is designed for general use and allows more direct editing of the data
      in those files, and does not require that each table have the same list of
      identifiers.</p>
    <p id="iii-p3">To edit a file first open it with the 'Open' command on the 'File' menu.
    </p>
    <p id="iii-p5">Table Editor will show a list of the&nbsp; tables available in the file.</p>
    <p id="iii-p7"><b>Table Panel:</b></p>
    <p id="iii-p9"> Select a table, and click 'Load' to open that table for editing. Click
      'Save' to save changes to the table before clicking 'Close' which will
      close the loaded table without saving any changes.<br>
    </p>
    <p id="iii-p11">To add a new table enter a name in the box provided, and click 'Add'.
      Click 'Load' to open the new table for editing.</p>
    <p id="iii-p13">Clicking 'Delete' will delete any selected table.</p>
    <p id="iii-p15">Values are edited by clicking the item in the list at the of the
      application frame. </p>
    <p id="iii-p17"><b>Identifiers Panel:</b><br>
      String identifiers can only be added, or deleted when a table is loaded.
      And are only added to the loaded table.</p>
    <p id="iii-p19">Enter an identifier and click 'Add' after loading a table to add a new
      identifier.</p>
    <p id="iii-p21">Clicking 'Delete' will delete any selected identifier from the loaded
      table.</p>
    <p id="iii-p23"> Values are edited by clicking the item in the list at the of the top of
      the application frame.</p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Theme Editor" id="iv">
<p id="iv-p1">Sower Theme Editor is used to create, and edit themes for
      Sower software. A theme is simply a list of images to be used for gui
      element of the user interface, and each image is associated with a string
      identifier. The theme file is named 'themes.sdf' which can be found in the
      software's data directory + 'themes'. For MS Windows this will be the
      directory where the application resides. Images should be in the png
      format, and 16X16 pixels. To create a new theme first create a sub-folder
      in Sower's theme directory, place the images for the theme in that folder.
      Then start Theme Editor, open 'themes.sdf', add a new table with the name
      of the new theme. Select the new table, and click 'Load'. Once the new
      table is loaded right click on any identifier in the list at the top of
      application frame to set the image for that identifier.</p>
    <p id="iv-p3"><b>Table Panel:</b></p>
    <p id="iv-p5">
 Select a table, and click 'Load' to open that table for editing. Click
      'Save' to save changes to the table before clicking 'Close' which will
      close the loaded table without saving any changes.</p>
    <p id="iv-p7">To add a new theme table enter a name in the box provided, and click
      'Add'. Click 'Load' to open the new table for editing.</p>
    <p id="iv-p9">Clicking 'Delete' will delete any selected table.</p>
    <p id="iv-p11">Values are edited by clicking the item in the list at the top of the
      application frame.</p>
    <p id="iv-p13"><b>Identifiers Panel:</b></p>
    <p id="iv-p15">
 String identifiers can only be added, or deleted when no tables are
      loaded. String identifiers when added are added to all tables, and when
      deleted are deleted from all tables.</p>
    <p id="iv-p17">Enter an identifier and click 'Add' when there no loaded tables to add a
      new identifier.</p>
    <p id="iv-p19">
 Clicking 'Delete' will delete any selected identifier from all tables.
    </p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Translation Editor" id="v">
<p id="v-p1">Sower Translation Editor is used to edit translation files for Sower
      software. The translation file for user interface elements is named
      'guitranslation.sdf', and for maps 'maptranslation.sdf', which be found in
      the software's data directory.</p>
    <p id="v-p3">To edit a translation file first open it with the 'Open' command on the
      'File' menu.</p>
    <p id="v-p5">Translation Editor will show a list of the translation tables available
      in the file.</p>
    <p id="v-p7"><b>Table Panel:</b></p>
    <p id="v-p9">
 Select a table, and click 'Load' to open that table for editing. Click
      'Save' to save changes to the table before clicking 'Close' which will
      close the loaded table without saving any changes.</p>
    <p id="v-p11">To add a new translation table select a language from the choices
      provided, and click 'Add'. Click 'Load' to open the new table for editing.</p>
    <p id="v-p13">Clicking 'Delete' will delete any selected table.</p>
    <p id="v-p15">Values are edited by clicking the item in the list at the top of the
      application frame.</p>
    <p id="v-p17"><b>Identifiers Panel:</b></p>
    <p id="v-p19">
 String identifiers can only be added, or deleted when no tables are
      loaded. String identifiers when added are added to all tables, and when
      deleted are deleted from all tables.</p>
    <p id="v-p21">Enter an identifier and click 'Add' when there no loaded tables to add a
      new identifier.</p>
    <p id="v-p23">
 Clicking 'Delete' will delete any selected identifier from all tables.
    </p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Help" id="vi">
<p id="vi-p1">Sower applications are designed to be cross-platform, and so
      a cross-platform solution for application help files was needed. The solution is Sower Help, which is a Sower application that loads only
      Sower modules with a category setting of 'Help'. Help modules are built from ThML files like all other other Sower modules,
      and have the same capabilities as other modules (such as streaming media, and AutoDef functionality).</p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Configuration" id="vii">
<p id="vii-p1">SowerBase can be configured to search for resources in specific locations
      through a file named 'sw_configure.sdf'. Settings in this file will
      override all other settings, and must exist in the application directory.
      This could be used to run Sower applications from a usb device, or to
      share resources such as modules between operating systems on the same
      computer. This file can be created, and edited with Sower Table Editor.
      Settings must exist in a table named according to the operating system on
      which it is to be used. These names are MSW, Linux, and MacOs. To add a
      setting use an identifier from the first column in the table below and set
      the 'Data' parameter to the desired value.</p>
