<div1 title="Sower Module Writer" id="viii">
<p id="viii-p1"> Sower Module Writer creates modules from ThML files.</p>
    <p id="viii-p3">Steps to module creation:</p>
    <ul id="viii-p4.1">
 <li id="viii-p4.2">Select the source file.</li>
      <li id="viii-p4.4">Select the destination file.</li>
      <li id="viii-p4.6">Enter the title of the book, and an abbreviation to be used to
        represent the book.</li>
      <li id="viii-p4.8">Enter an identifier for the book. This should be something such as a
        ISBN number if available. It must be unique.</li>
      <li id="viii-p4.10">Select the category that best fits the book.</li>
      <li id="viii-p4.12">Enter any group that applies to the book. Such as a particular author.</li>
      <li id="viii-p4.14">And if applicable enter the versification scheme used by the book,
        such as 'KJV'.</li>
      <li id="viii-p4.16">Enter the original file name of the source file in the box provided.
        This maybe used to follow links between books. Enter only the file name,
        do not include the file path.</li>
      <li id="viii-p4.18">Sower Modules can be encrypted. If the encryption plug-in is available
        the 'Encrypt' box will be enabled which can be checked and will enable a
        password to be entered. The module will be encrypted, and a master key
        will be created and stored in Sower's data folder
        (data-dir\keys\master). Copy commands to content viewers that are
        displaying any content of this module can be disabled by unchecking the
        box labeled 'Allow Copy'.</li>
    </ul>
    <p id="viii-p5">Click 'Build'.</p>
    <p id="viii-p7">Five files will be created the module (.smd), a bzipped file containing
      the compressed module (.bz2), a catalog card that contains information for
      the module so that it doesn't have to be entered again if the module is
      rebuilt (.card), and an html file which displays the full title of the
      module in that folder (Title.html). It is best for&nbsp; ThML files to be
      stored in it's own folder. A log file containing containing the results of
      the build process (.log.txt).</p>
    <p id="viii-p9">During the build process error messages may be displayed. For most error
      messages the portion of the text in the source file that caused the error
      will follow the error code so that the problem can be located in the
      source file.</p>
    <table id="viii-p10.1" style="width: 100%" border="1">
 <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.2" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">1.
            EC_UNCONTAINED_TEXT_RUN</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.4" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">Some portion of text
            is not contained in an element other than the '&lt;divN&gt;' that it
            exists in.</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.6" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">Possible cause:<br>
            &lt;div1&gt;text&lt;/div1&gt;<br>
            <br>
            Solution:<br>
            &lt;div1&gt;&lt;p&gt;text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div1&gt;</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.8" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">2.
            EC_UNCONTAINED_SCRIPTURE</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.10" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">A scripture element
            does not have a mate.</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.12" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">Possible cause:<br>
            &lt;scripture/&gt;verse text<br>
            <br>
            Solution:<br>
            &lt;scripture&gt;verse text&lt;/scripture&gt;</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.14" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">3.
            EC_UNCONTAINED_COMMENTARY</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.16" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">A scripCom element
            does not have a mate.</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.18" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">Possible cause:<br>
            &lt;scripCom/&gt;commentary text<br>
            <br>
            Solution:<br>
            &lt;scripCom&gt;verse text&lt;/scripCom&gt;</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.20" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">4.
            EC_UNABLE_TO_IDENTIFY_ID</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.22" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;" rowspan="3" colspan="1">4,
            - 6 all represent a situation where the scripture represented by an
            id could not be identified.</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.24" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;" rowspan="3" colspan="1">Possible
            cause:<br>
            This is most likely due to an unrecognized book name, or
            abbreviation.<br>
            <br>
            Solution:<br>
            Replace with one that is known to work.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.26" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">5.
            EC_UNABLE_TO_IDENTIFY_PASSAGE</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.28" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">6.
            EC_UNABLE_TO_IDENTIFY_OSISID</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.30" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">7.
            EC_UNABLE_TO_LOCATE_EXTERNAL_FILE</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.32" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">A file referenced in
            the source file can not be located, and has not been included in the
            module.</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.34" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">Possible cause:<br>
            A missing, or misplaced file such as an image has been referenced in
            the source file.<br>
            <br>
            Solution:<br>
            Locate the file and put it in the proper place in relation to the
            source file.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.36" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">8.
            EC_UNABLE_TO_LOAD_EXTERNAL_FILE</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.38" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">A file referenced in
            the source file has been located, but can not be read.</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.40" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">Possible cause:<br>
            Another application may have the file open, and is preventing other
            applications from accessing the file.<br>
            <br>
            Solution:<br>
            Close any applications that may be using the file.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.42" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">9.
            EC_CORRUPT_ITEM_DATA</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.44" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">An internal error has
            occurred.</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.46" style="width: 33%; background-color: white;">Possible cause:<br>
            Unknown.<br>
            <br>
            Solution:<br>
            Rebuild the module.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="viii-p10.48">10. EC_POSSIBLE_ENTITY_ENCODING_ERROR</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.50">This is considered as a warning, as it is not certain that it is
            an error.</td>
          <td id="viii-p10.52">Possible cause:<br>
            A '#' character has been found in a text run, and has been followed
            with at least one digit, and a semicolon. And is not preceded by an
            ampersand character. Which it must be if it is actually an encoded
            character.<br>
            <br>
            Solution:<br>
            Insert '&amp;' before the '#'.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Librarian" id="ix">
<p id="ix-p1">Sower Librarian is a tool designed to create, and maintain a library of
      Sower Modules built from ThML files. It scans the selected folder, and
      sub-folders searching for ThML files, and corresponding modules. It
      compares file dates and skips any that appear to be current. If a module
      has been built before there should be a card file for the module. If there
      is a card file and the module needs to be rebuilt it is done without
      requiring any user interaction. This minimizes the need for user input
      when updating an existing library. A password can be entered for any
      modules that require encryption. The same password will be used for all
      encrypted modules. If a modules requires encryption and a password has not
      been entered the module will be skipped. It is similar in operation to
      Sower Module Writer, and creates the same files with the exception that it
      creates one log file for all modules in the root folder of the library
      instead of a log file for each module.</p>
   <p id="ix-p3">Encryption is only available if the encryption plug-in is available. At
      this point in time that plug-in has not been released.</p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Module Inspector" id="x">
<p id="x-p1">Sower Module Inspector is a utility to examine modules created with Sower
      Module Writer. </p>
    <ol id="x-p2.1">
 <li id="x-p2.2">The module header.</li>
      <li id="x-p2.4">The table of contents.</li>
      <li id="x-p2.6">The media contents, external files referenced in the source file that
        have been automatically included in the module.</li>
      <li id="x-p2.8">Scripture elements that have been identified in the source file. These
        are not presented in a list, to verify this enter a reference in the box
        provided and click the 'Find' button such as 'Gen. 1:1'.</li>
      <li id="x-p2.10">ScripCom elements that have been identified in the source file. Check
        for entries as with Scripture elements.</li>
      <li id="x-p2.12">Strongs Greek entries.</li>
      <li id="x-p2.14">Strongs Hebrew entries.</li>
      <li id="x-p2.16">Terms (entries) in dictionaries, or encyclopedias.</li>
      <li id="x-p2.18">Notes, a complete list of notes identified in the source file.</li>
    </ol>
    <p id="x-p3">For encrypted modules there must be a master key, or a user key
      available to open the module.</p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="ThML Builder" id="xii">
<p id="xii-p1">ThML Builder is a utility designed to create a ThML file from multiple
      html files. The resulting file may require further editing. It is intended
      to reduce some of the work required to convert a multi-file html book to
      ThML.</p>
    <p id="xii-p3">To create a ThML file:</p>
    <ul id="xii-p4.1">
 <li id="xii-p4.2">Enter any information that should be stored in the dublin core of the
        file.</li>
      <li id="xii-p4.4">Click the 'Select files' button to select the files to be used in the
        build.</li>
      <li id="xii-p4.6">Select or enter the 'Save as' file path.</li>
      <li id="xii-p4.8">Uncheck any files in the list that should not be included in the
        build.</li>
      <li id="xii-p4.10">Use the 'Up', and 'Down' buttons to position the files according to
        the desired contents of the resulting ThML file.</li>
      <li id="xii-p4.12">Click 'Build'.</li>
    </ul>
    <p id="xii-p5">ThML Builder can also load a Sower Project file which describes how to
      build the ThML file. This method allows for the creation of more complex
      books. And also provides options for automatic markup of scripture
      references.</p>
    <ul id="xii-p6.1">
 </ul>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Map Editor" id="xiii">
<p id="xiii-p1">Sower Map Editor is a utility for creating Image Maps (a list of points
      on an image) which can be included in Sower Modules, and related to a
      specific image. It does not edit the image itself.</p>
    <p id="xiii-p3">The items (map areas) in the image map specify the position of a point on
      the image, name, draw color, fill color, and radius. AutoDef uses the name
      to locate information related to the area to display in an AutoDef window.
      If a translation file is available the name of the area can be translated
      and displayed in a tooltip window, or used to find information for AutoDef
      in a different language.</p>
    <p id="xiii-p5">Image Maps can be automatically generated with user input for approximate
      pixels positions of latitude, and longitude of&nbsp; 4 positions on the
      map image. These are top, bottom, left, and right. And do not have to be
      the absolute corners, but as close as possible for greatest accuracy. The
      generated map areas can be edited manually if needed. Image Maps are
      stored in an Image Map List, allowing multiple Image Maps for the image to
      be stored in one Sower Binary Object. </p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Module Installer" id="xiv">
<p id="xiv-p1">Sower Module Installer decompresses bzipped modules into the Sower Modules directory. This utility is provided to make it easier for users who may not know where the module library is on their system.</p> 
</div1>

<div1 title="Sower Project Writer" id="xv">
<p id="xv-p1"> Sower Project Writer creates a Sower Project file from opf files used in epub books.
     ThML Writer can then be used to create a ThML file of the ebook. The target should be a file name without extension for the project file that will be generated. This file will be created in the same directory as the opf file.<br>
     This name will also be used for the ThML file that is to be created from the project file.</p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Markup Editor" id="xvi">
<p id="xvi-p1">Sower Markup Editor is a text based markup editor.  Elements for Html, ThML, and SwPrjML
      can be entered by selecting an item from a list. If there is a text selection the open, and closing
       tags will enclose the selection. When a mouse hovers over an element AutoDef will provide
       information about the element if any information is available in installed Sower Modules.</p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Sower Project Markup Language" id="xvii">
<p id="xvii-p1">Sower Project Markup Language is a markup language which specifies how a
      ThML file is to be created from one or more files. The table below
      describes the elements. All elements are processed in the order listed in
      the project file.</p>
    <table id="xvii-p2.1" style="width: 100%;" border="1">
 <thead id="xvii-p2.2">
 <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.3">Element</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.5">Description</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.7">Attributes</td>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.10">body</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.12">Represents where the body of the ThML file begins, and ends.</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.14">none</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.16">div1</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.18" rowspan="6" colspan="1">div1 through div6 represent a division,
            and depth in the text as in ThML.</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.20" rowspan="6" colspan="1">src - the relative path to the file that
            contains the content for the division.<br>
            title - the title for the division.<br>
            id - the id for the division.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.22">div2</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.24">div3</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.26">div4</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.28">div5</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.30">div6</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.32">file</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.34">A file that is to be copied to the current position of the ThML
            file.</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.36">src - the relative path to the file.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.38">head</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.40">Represents where the head of the ThML file begins, and ends.</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.42">none</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.44">info</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.46">Represents where the electronic information of the ThML file
            begins, and ends.</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.48">none</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.50">project</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.52">Begins, and ends a project file.</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.54">target - relative path for the ThML file that is to be created.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.56">references</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.58">Defines if scripture references should be processed, and the rules
            to recognize those references. Enforcing strict rules will help
            prevent inaccurate markup.</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.60">process - true to process references, otherwise false.<br>
            cvdiv - marker that is exists between chapter, and verse numbers.
            Typically ':'.<br>
            span - marker that represents a span in a reference. Typically '-'.<br>
            div - marker that represents a division in a reference. Typically
            ','.<br>
            break - marker that represents a break in a reference. Typically
            ';'.<br>
            romanforchapters - true if chapter numbers are roman numerals, false
            otherwise.<br>
            romanforverses - true if verse numbers are roman numerals, false
            otherwise.<br>
            romanlowercase - true if roman numerals are only valid if lower
            case, otherwise false.<br>
            booknameuppercase - true if book names must always begin with a
            capital letter, otherwise false.<br>
            linebreakisspace - line breaks should be treated as space
            characters. This should be false for text files, and true for
            most&nbsp; markup languages.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.62">style</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.64">Represents where any css style information begins, and ends.</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.66">none</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td id="xvii-p2.68">verbatim</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.70">Text enclosed in the 'verbatim' element will be copied verbatim to
            the target file.</td>
          <td id="xvii-p2.72">none</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p id="xvii-p3">Project file example:</p>
    <p id="xvii-p5">&lt;project target="book.thm"&gt;<br>
      &lt;references process="true" cvdiv=":" span="-" div="," break=";"
      romanforchapters="true" romanforverses="false" romanlowercase="true"
      booknameuppercase="true" linebreakisspace="true"/&gt;<br>
      &lt;head&gt;<br>
      &lt;info&gt;<br>
      &lt;verbatim&gt;<br>
      --Dublin Core Text--<br>
      &lt;/verbatim&gt;<br>
      &lt;/info&gt;<br>
      &lt;style&gt;<br>
      &lt;file src="book.css"/&gt;<br>
      &lt;/style&gt;<br>
      &lt;/head&gt;<br>
      &lt;body&gt;<br>
      &lt;div1 src="chapter1.htm" title="Chapter 1" id="i"/&gt;<br>
      &lt;/body&gt;<br>
      &lt;/project&gt;</p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="SowerBase" id="xviii">
<p id="xviii-p1">SowerBase is a cross-platform dynamic link library, or shared object
      designed to provide the foundation code for Sower applications. Some of it's
      capabilities are:</p>
    <ul id="xviii-p2.1">
 <li id="xviii-p2.2">Handles theme, translation, bookmark, and preferences files for
        applications.</li>
      <li id="xviii-p2.4">Provides facilities for working with Html, and ThML.</li>
      <li id="xviii-p2.6">Recognizes scripture references in multiple languages, and forms.</li>
      <li id="xviii-p2.8">GeoLocation data for working with maps of the ancient world.</li>
      <li id="xviii-p2.10">Provides a very versatile book module design, and the facilities to
        work with those modules.</li>
      <li id="xviii-p2.12">Provides a gui frame work on top of the wxWidgets frame work, reducing
        much of the work involved in handling windows, menus, and toolbars.
        Including specialized controls designed to work with Sower modules, ThML
        files, and automatically update themselves for language, or theme
        changes.</li>
      <li id="xviii-p2.14">Plug-In, and module managers.</li>
      <li id="xviii-p2.16">Initialization of applications, and SowerBase itself.</li>
    </ul>
    <p id="xviii-p3">And more. Greatly reducing the complexity of writing document driven
      software that works with ThML files, or Sower modules.</p>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Additional Information For Building Modules" id="xix">
<p id="xix-p1">Sower Modules are built from ThML files (Theological Markup Language),
      and although ThML is specifically designed for theological texts it is
      suited to almost any type of book. More information on ThML can be found
      at www.ccel.org.</p>
    <p id="xix-p3">There are a few Sower specific extensions to ThML:</p>
    <ol id="xix-p4.1">
 <li id="xix-p4.2">Div1 - Div6 can have an extra attribute named 'type' which causes a
        specific content viewer to be used for display if a viewer of that type
        is available. The possible values for 'type' are:<br>
        <ul id="xix-p4.3">
 <li id="xix-p4.4"> Text</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.6"> ThML</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.8"> Html</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.10"> Hymn</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.12"> Lesson</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.14"> Image</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.16"> Map</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.18"> Audio</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.20"> Video</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.22"> 2D</li>
          <li id="xix-p4.24"> 3D</li>
        </ul>
        <p id="xix-p5"> ThML is the default, and does not need to be specified. </p>
      </li>
      <li id="xix-p6.2"> An 'geodata' attribute can be added to the html 'img' element and
        should 6 variables. And should take this form:<br>
        geodata="width in px, height in px, latitude top, latitude bottom,
        longitude left, longitude right"<br>
        This will cause SowerBase to use internal geolocation data to identify
        places at the position of the mouse and display data associated with the
        place if any has been found.</li>
      <li id="xix-p6.4">(img, audio, video, music, and source) elements can be used to cause
        media files to be stored in the module.<br>
        &lt;audio&gt;<br>
        &lt;source src="sample-15s.wav" type="audio/wav"&gt;<br>
        &lt;/audio&gt; <br>
        &nbsp; <audio id="xix-p6.5" controls="controls"> <source id="xix-p6.6" src="sample-15s.wav" type="audio/wav">
        </audio></li>
      <li id="xix-p6.9">The Sower specific 'interface' element can be used to for Sower Binary
        Object files to be stored in the module using a relative path as in the
        'img' element.</li>
      <li id="xix-p6.11">A Sower specific element 'term.strongs' is intended for use in markup
        of lexicons. Used in place of the ThML 'term' element. It has 3
        attributes, value (strongs number followed with a G, or H depending on
        the language), translit (english transliteration of the original word),
        origin (the word in the original language).</li>
      <li id="xix-p6.13">A Sower specific element 'christ' can be used to mark Christ's words
        in scripture.</li>
    </ol>
  </div1>

<div1 title="Credits" id="xx">
<p id="xx-p1">Sower Applications are developed with CodeBlocks, and gcc. Using
      wxWidgets for user interface elements, MiniAudio for audio, and libbz2 for
      file compression.</p>
	<p id="xx-p3">All of Sower Applications has been designed to work with ThML files as defined in ThML 1.04.htm which
	can be found at 'https://www.ccel.org/ThML/ThML1.04.htm' . The reference information in thml.smd
	comes from the same file. To learn more go to ccel.org .</p>
